  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why I cannot use netsend commands?",
  "response": "The `net send` command was a feature in older versions of Windows (such as Windows XP) that allowed users to send messages to other users or computers on the same network using the **Messenger Service**. However, this command was deprecated and removed in later versions of Windows (starting with Windows Vista) for several reasons:\n\n### Reasons Why You Cannot Use `net send`:\n1. **Deprecated Feature**:\n   - The Messenger Service, which `net send` relied on, was considered a security risk. It could be exploited by spammers and malicious users to send unsolicited messages (e.g., pop-ups) to other computers on the network.\n   - Microsoft decided to disable and remove this service in later versions of Windows.\n\n2. **Replaced by More Secure Tools**:\n   - Microsoft introduced more secure and modern alternatives for messaging and communication, such as:\n     - **Net Send Replacement**: `msg` command (available in Command Prompt).\n     - **Third-Party Tools**: Applications like Microsoft Teams, Slack, or other messaging platforms.\n     - **Remote Administration Tools**: PowerShell and other scripting tools for network management.\n\n3. **Compatibility Issues**:\n   - The `net send` command is not supported in modern versions of Windows (Windows Vista, 7, 8, 10, or 11). If you try to use it, you'll likely get an error message like:\n     ```\n     'net send' is not recognized as an internal or external command, operable program, or batch file.\n     ```\n\n---\n\n### Alternatives to `net send`:\nIf you need to send messages or notifications to other users on the same network, here are some alternatives:\n\n1. **`msg` Command**:\n   - Available in Command Prompt on modern Windows versions.\n   - Example:\n     ```\n     msg username \"Your message here\"\n     ```\n\n2. **PowerShell**:\n   - Use PowerShell to send messages or notifications.\n   - Example:\n     ```powershell\n     Send-MailMessage -To \"user@example.com\" -From \"admin@example.com\" -Subject \"Test Message\" -Body \"This is a test message.\"\n     ```\n\n3. **Third-Party Tools**:\n   - Use modern messaging tools like Microsoft Teams, Slack, or other network communication software.\n\n4. **Networking Tools**:\n   - Use network management tools or scripts to communicate with other computers on the network.\n\n---\n\n### Conclusion:\nThe `net send` command is no longer available in modern Windows versions due to security concerns and advancements in technology. Instead, use the `msg` command or other modern tools for messaging and communication.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
